ks how the passage of time in the Low Countries was ordered by the rhythms of human action, from the musical life of a cathedral to the measurement of time by clocks and calendars, the work habits of a guildsman to the devotional practices of the laity and religious orders. Through a series of transdisciplinary case studies, it explores the multiple ways that objects, texts and music might themselves be said to engage with, imply, and unsettle time, shaping and forming the lives of the inhabitants of the fifteenth-century Low Countries. Champion reframes the ways historians have traditionally told the history of time, allowing us for the first time to understand the rich and varied interplay of temporalities in the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aFifteenth century. 0aTime perceptionxSocial aspectszBenelux countries. 0aTimexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aTimexSocial aspectszBenelux countries. 0aTime--Social aspects--Benelux countries. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aLow Countries.  acalendar.  achronology.  afifteenth century.  aliturgy.  amedieval.  amusic.  atemporality.  atime.  avision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226514826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226514826/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles